#Text=ALL FOUND
#Text=I had seen her but once before , and that was at the Savoy on New Year 's Eve .
#Text=She had been with her party at one table , and I with mine at another .
#Text=And in the midst of the reveling I had chanced to look up and into one of the great mirrors which made a panel upon the wall .
#Text=There I had seen the girl , sitting back in her chair , smiling and fresh and white-shouldered , in a dress of black and gold , her fingers about the stem of her goblet .
#Text=Not talking , listening , rather , to the words of a man at her side , whose eyes were watching her smiling lips somewhat greedily .
#Text=He had red hair , I remember , and a moustache brushed up to hide a long upper lip .
#Text=And , as I looked , she also had looked up , and our eyes had met .
#Text=There and then I had raised my wine and toasted her -- her of the looking-glass .
#Text=The smile had deepened .
#Text=Then she had raised her glass , and drunk to me in return .
#Text=That was all .
#Text=And when Berry had leaned across the table and asked :
#Text=" Who 's your friend ? "
#Text=" I wish I knew . "
#Text=" Pshaw ! " said my brother-in-law .
#Text=" I say it deliberately . "
#Text=" I drank to a thought , " said I.
#Text=" Believe me . "
#Text=After all , a thought is a reflection .
#Text=And now here she was , sitting in the grass by the wayside .
#Text=" She 's brown , is n't she ? " said I.
#Text=" As a berry .

column1: #Text=" But- "
#Text=" But what ? "
#Text=" ' Quis custodiet -- ' "
#Text=The apple she threw passed over my shoulder .

#Text=Mountains and valleys , swift rivers and curling roads , here and there a village shining in the hot sun , and once in a while a castle in the woods , white-walled , red-roofed , peaceful enough now in its old age , but hinting at wild oats sown and reaped when it was young .
#Text=Hinting broadly , too .

#Text=At nights shaken with the flare of torches and the clash of arms , at oaths and laughter and the tinkle of spurs on the worn steps , at threats and bloodlettings and all the good old ways , now dead , out of date , and less indebted to memory than imagination .

#Text=And then at galleries with creaking floors , at arras and the rustle of a dress ; whisperings , too , and the proud flash of eyes , hands lily-white , whose fingers men must kiss and in the eyes mirror themselves .
#Text=But these things are not dead .
#Text=Old-fashioned wrath is over -- gone to its long home : love is not even wrinkled .
#Text=Yet again it was before wrath ...

#Text=I set out to describe the province of Krain , and now I have strayed from the highway up one of those curling roads to one of those white castles , only to lose myself in the thicket of Romance beyond .
#Text=Perhaps it does not matter .
#Text=Anyway , it was on the slope of a green meadow all among the mountains of Krain that the girl was sitting , herself unminded , minding her cows .
#Text=And out of the woods above her a round , white tower proclaimed a chateau set on the shoulder of a hill .
#Text=Her dress was that of the country , and yet , perhaps , rather such as Croatian peasants wear .

#Text=All white linen , embroidered ever so richly , cut low and round at the neck , and with the skirt falling some four inches below her knee : short sleeves , a small , white apron , and over her thick , fair hair a bright red kerchief .
#Text=But her stockings were of white silk , and small , black buckled slippers kept the little feet .
#Text=Clear , blue eyes hers , and a small merry mouth , and a skin after the sun 's own heart .
#Text=It was so brown -- such an even , delicate brown .
#Text=Brown cheeks and temples , brown arms and hands , brown throat .
#Text=Oh , very picturesque .
#Text=I rounded up the cow errant , returned to my lady , and took my seat by her side .
#Text=" Thank you , " she said .
#Text=" And now , who are you and what do you want ? "
#Text=" My name , " said I , " is Norval .

#Text=" I know we 're both mad , " said she .
#Text=" And I do n't feel a bit like singing really , either . "
